    content:
      '<p class="leading-relaxed mb-6">The road to Jibhi was a ribbon of ice and uncertainty. Our driver—a man named Suresh who\'d been doing this route for twenty years—navigated the hairpin turns like he was born on them. The higher we climbed, the whiter everything became. By the time we reached the village, it was snowing. Not the gentle flurries you see in movies. Proper mountain snow that accumulates while you watch.</p><p class="mb-6">Jibhi is tiny. A handful of wooden houses, two shops, and one homestay that looked like it had grown out of the mountainside. I stomped the snow off my boots and stepped inside to find a fire crackling and the smell of cinnamon. The owner, a soft-spoken woman named Meera, handed me a cup of ginger tea and said <q class="text-amber-600 italic">You made it.</q> Like it was an achievement. Maybe it was.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">The First Snowfall</h2><p class="mb-6">I woke up to a world transformed. Everything was white—the pine trees, the rooftops, the narrow paths that led to nowhere. I layered up and stepped outside. The silence was the first thing I noticed. Not the absence of sound, but the presence of stillness. Snow absorbs everything, I learned. Your footsteps, your voice, your worries. All of it just settles, soft and white and quiet.</p><blockquote class="italic text-stone-600 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-6 my-8 text-lg font-light">"Winter in the mountains doesn\'t just freeze the ground. It freezes time. And sometimes that\'s exactly what you need."</blockquote><p class="mb-6">I walked to the waterfall—the one they told me about—frozen mid-flow, a curtain of ice hanging from the rocks. A flock of birds flew overhead, leaving no footprints, and I stood there wondering if I was the only person in the world. Not in a lonely way. In a peaceful way.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">Evenings By The Fire</h2><p class="mb-6">The evenings were my favorite. I\'d sit by the fire with a book and watch the snow fall outside the window. Meera would bring me dinner—simple food that tasted like care: dal, rice, and a vegetable curry she\'d grown in her garden. She\'d sit with me sometimes, telling me stories about the village, about the floods that had come and gone, about the tourists who visited in summer and never returned.</p><p class="mb-6">On my last night, the sky cleared. I walked outside and looked up at the stars. I\'ve never seen so many. The Milky Way was a river of light, the mountains dark silhouettes against it. I stood there until my nose went numb, trying to hold onto the moment. But you can\'t hold onto moments. You can only live them.</p><p class="italic text-stone-600 mt-8">I left Jibhi with snow in my hair and winter in my heart. Some places don\'t change you—they remind you of who you already are.</p>',
