    coverImage:
      "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1664150543913-66f20bf84ba9?q=80&w=1032&auto=format&fit=crop&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D",
    content:
      '<p class="leading-relaxed mb-6">I\'d seen photos of the Rann of Kutch—the white salt desert stretching to infinity—but photographs lie. They flatten it, make it look like a painting. The real thing is more alive. The wind doesn\'t stop. The salt crunches under your feet. And the silence isn\'t an absence of sound; it\'s a presence. Like the desert is breathing.</p><p class="mb-6">I arrived at sunset. The sky had turned the color of mangoes, and the white salt reflected it back, doubling the light, doubling the beauty. A group of women in bright ghagras walked across the marsh, their shadows long and blue. They were carrying water, I realized. The same water their mothers had carried, and their grandmothers before them. The Rann doesn\'t give—you have to take.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">The Moonrise</h2><p class="mb-6">The next night, I returned. This time alone. The full moon rose over the salt flat, and the entire Rann turned silver. I walked until I couldn\'t see the edge anymore. No tracks behind me, no tracks ahead. Just me and the moon and the white earth. I sat down and listened. The wind was different here—it carried stories. Stories of traders crossing this desert on camelback. Stories of lovers who\'d met under this same moon. Stories of the earth itself, forming and reforming for millennia.</p><blockquote class="italic text-stone-600 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-6 my-8 text-lg font-light">"The Rann doesn\'t care about your plans. It cares about your presence. Stay long enough, and it will tell you its secrets."</blockquote><p class="mb-6">I stayed for three hours, watching the moon arc across the sky. At some point, I stopped counting time. The desert has a way of doing that—stretching moments until they feel like eternities. When I finally walked back, my footprints were the only marks on the white canvas. By morning, they\'d be gone.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">The Village Women</h2><p class="mb-6">The real heart of Kutch is in its villages. I spent a day in a tiny hamlet where women embroider geometric patterns onto fabric—the kind of artistry that takes a lifetime to perfect. An old woman named Jaya showed me how to stitch a mirror onto cloth. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">For good luck,</q> she said, smiling. Her hands were gnarled with age, but they moved like they were young. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">This is how we remember who we are. In the stitches. In the colors.</q></p><p class="mb-6">She fed me roti with a spicy pickle that burned my tongue and a sweet jaggery that cooled it. Her grandchildren played in the dust, chasing chickens, laughing. The afternoon sun was harsh, but under her thatched roof, it was cool and dark and peaceful. I asked if she ever wanted to leave. She laughed. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">Where would I go? The desert is my home. It raised me. It will bury me.</q></p><p class="mb-6">On my last day, I stood at the edge of the Rann one more time. The wind was picking up, carrying salt and sand and the faint smell of something I couldn\'t name. I thought about the women and their embroidery, about the moon and the silver light, about all the footprints that had been erased before mine. The Rann doesn\'t keep records. It just keeps going.</p><p class="italic text-stone-600 mt-8">I left Kutch with salt in my shoes and a stillness in my chest. The desert had taught me something: permanence is an illusion. All we have is the moment. And the moment, like the salt, is white and infinite and beautiful.</p>',
