    coverImage:
      "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1593813738953-fb3c93e0769d?q=80&w=954&auto=format&fit=crop&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D",
    content:
      '<p class="leading-relaxed mb-6">The taxi from Shillong wound through hills so green they seemed to glow. The driver—a cheerful man named Boris—kept pointing at things. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">That\'s a waterfall,</q> he\'d say, or <q class="text-amber-600 italic">That village has the best pork.</q> Everything was wet. The leaves, the roads, the air itself. Meghalaya means "the abode of clouds," and the clouds were living up to their reputation. They hung low, brushing the treetops, filling the valleys with mist that looked like milk.</p><p class="mb-6">I came for the living root bridges. These aren\'t built; they\'re grown. The Khasi people have spent centuries training the roots of rubber trees across rivers, creating bridges that get stronger with age. I\'d seen photos, but standing on one was different. The roots were thick as my arm, twisting and braiding into a living structure that pulsed with—well, I don\'t know if it pulsed, but it felt alive. Because it was.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">The Double-Decker Bridge</h2><p class="mb-6">The trek to the famous double-decker root bridge was 3,000 steps down. Down, down, down through jungle so thick the sun struggled to reach the ground. Cicadas screamed. Birds called in languages I couldn\'t understand. And then, through the trees, I saw it—two bridges stacked on top of each other, the roots cascading like water frozen in wood. I stood there for a long time, just staring. A local guide named Kynsai told me the bridge had taken over a hundred years to grow. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">Our grandfathers planted it,</q> he said. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">Our grandchildren will use it.</q></p><blockquote class="italic text-stone-600 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-6 my-8 text-lg font-light">"When you walk on a living root bridge, you\'re not just crossing a river. You\'re walking through time itself."</blockquote><p class="mb-6">I crossed the bridge slowly, feeling the roots flex under my weight. Below, the river was clear and cold. A boy was fishing with a handmade net. He waved. I waved back. The bridge didn\'t seem to notice—it had seen thousands of crossings, carried thousands of lives. One more didn\'t matter.</p><h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-stone-800 mt-10 mb-4">The Wettest Place</h2><p class="mb-6">The next day, I went to Mawsynram—the wettest place on earth. It wasn\'t raining when I arrived, which the locals assured me was rare. <q class="text-amber-600 italic">You\'re lucky,</q> they said. But I wanted to see the rain. I wanted to understand what 11,000 millimetres of annual rainfall looked like. And then, around noon, it came. Not drops—sheets. The sky opened and the world turned gray and silver and white. I stood on a balcony and watched the water fall. It wasn\'t violent. It was relentless. Like the sky had decided it would never stop.</p><p class="mb-6">I was drenched in seconds. But I stayed. I stayed because the rain wasn\'t just water—it was the reason everything was so green. The reason the roots grew. The reason the clouds never left. It was Meghalaya\'s heartbeat.</p><p class="mb-6">I walked back to the village—a village of 500 people and 500 shades of green—and a woman offered me shelter. Her house was a wooden cottage. The rain drummed on the roof like applause. She gave me ginger tea with an egg, and we sat together watching the world dissolve into water. No English. No shared language. But she pointed at the rain and smiled, and I smiled back. Some things don\'t need words.</p><p class="italic text-stone-600 mt-8">Meghalaya taught me that clouds aren\'t just things in the sky. They\'re visitors, taking a break before moving on. And if you\'re lucky, you might get to host them for a while.</p>',
